english:
  title: A Memorial to Minister Jin Kangong
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I, Lee, Your Petitioner, Remonstrator of the Right and Keeper of the Imperial Seal, having chosen an auspicious date and purified myself through fasting, humbly present this memorial to your esteemed residence.

    When standing before you in direct questioning, I shrink into myself, unable to distinguish right from wrong. Later, when I have withdrawn, should words come to me, they would seem like those of one who chases after truth merely to dress it up—and such words would surely never gain your approval. Yet it is the nature of my character to be solitary and unbending, and I am one whose tongue fails him, unable to make myself understood before those of rank and honor. This is simply my lot. But perhaps I may use these inadequate words as a substitute for speech, to illuminate what lies in my heart. I humbly beg your consideration.

    There was a matter which you, sir, had long since decided and decreed. Yet the ministry knew it not. Then, from the side, came a contrary opinion that greatly opposed your judgment. Unable to restrain your anger, you summoned an official and questioned him about the source of this dissenting view. In that moment, beneath your terrible authority, the man trembled, sweat poured forth, and he knew not what to say. When you raised your voice and pressed him further, demanding speech, though he was bewildered and lost, his mind turned to one whom he had long harbored resentment against—and he named me. This came about because I had once, in the course of duty, sharply rebuked this very official. Thus was the blame cast upon me, and I have remained suspended from office these many days. I was seized with fear and dread, nearly overcome, before slowly recovering.

    Yet even if this opinion had come from me, it would be but a matter of official business. And as to whether such an opinion should be adopted or rejected—this rests solely with your judgment. For it is the very duty of officials in the ministry to propose and initiate discussion. The ministry keeps many positions precisely so that what one man has not conceived in his heart, another may conceive and propose; and what another has not thought of, the first may raise and champion. Thus do we stimulate one another, deliberate together, and gradually the will of the state comes forth. Should all merely look about nervously, fearing to be first to speak, how could any policy ever emerge? Who would first expose and correct the failings of the hundred officials? This is the very nature of our office and should not be deemed a crime.

    Moreover, as for this opinion—it did not originate with me. I could have named the man who truly proposed it, but I chose not to wound a colleague and friend by exposing him. Instead I withdrew quietly, without making the matter clear. And truly, there are greater crimes than this, which I would sooner bear myself than allow the fault to fall upon another. This is but a trifling matter of official business, touching not upon the welfare of the state, nor upon matters requiring bold independent judgment. Even should I bear blame for it, it should not be great. How could I, then, have the audacity to save myself by naming and denouncing another?

    I have heard it said that rise and fall, success and failure, are all bound to Heaven's will. Yet as I see it, my inability to defend myself in this present injustice stems only from my solitary nature, my stumbling tongue, and my stubborn refusal to harm my colleagues. Had I but spoken plainly, I would be free of this. Why invoke Heaven's will?

    Once there were two men traveling together—one swift of foot, one lame. When a man of rank approached, the swift one cursed him and fled in haste before the man could even raise his eyes. But the man of rank, supposing it was the lame one who had cursed him, seized and bound him, beat him severely, and then released him. Am I not like that lame man, bearing punishment for words I did not speak, simply because my nature is direct and my tongue slow?

    Yet I think: had this opinion been greatly beneficial and won your approval and reward, would that official have allowed me to bear the punishment silently in his stead? This is why, though I did not name him, neither can I accept this punishment with grace.

    But time reveals all things. With your discerning eye, if you examine this matter further, and transform your anger into the warmth of spring, then my present suspension would be like a tree not yet wholly withered—surely it could yet revive.

    How do I know this? At first, you wished to observe which officials possessed conscientiousness, so you tested and questioned them. Then, shortly after, you rejected that official, saying: "The duty of officials in the Remonstrance Office is to guard secrecy and prevent leaks. Though I was angry, I did not mean to impose death. I rejected this man because he divulged the source of the opinion—this was improper." When the officials of court heard this, all praised your righteousness, and none ceased singing your praises. From this I reckon that my punishment too will not culminate in great ruin. I can wait a while longer.

    Yet my stipend has ceased. If my whole household starves, how could the people of the realm understand? How could they know that I am not guilty of grave transgression? This is why I am driven to cry out in anguish.

    I humbly beseech you: recognize that this official acted from private resentment to harm a colleague. Understand that I bore reproach for another yet chose not to reveal him clearly, valuing my oath not to wound those around me. Take pity on one whose nature is upright but whose tongue stumbles, unable to defend his sincerity before you. With the clarity of a mirror, discern what is crooked and what is straight. Wash away this false accusation, and do not let me be like that lame man, beaten unjustly for words he did not speak.

    My body draws near to dust. I bow in waiting for your command. Ah, whether I rise or fall depends upon this day alone. I can bear this anxiety no longer. I have presumed upon your dignity. I remain, your humble servant, bowing twice.
  footnotes:
    - The 'lame man' parable is a recurring image in this memorial, symbolizing the injustice of bearing blame for another's actions due to one's own reticence and character flaws.
    - Lee Gyu-bo served as a Remonstrator (諫官), an official whose duty was to criticize imperial and ministerial actions. This memorial concerns his suspension from office due to accusations he cannot refute without betraying a colleague.
